Do you have a black box in your car?
While U.S. road designers are trying to find money to repair a depleted highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in a small black box that is neatly fitted to your car’s accessory panel.
These devices, tracking every mile a motorist travels and transmitting this information to officials, are at the heart of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated motorway financing system undertaken by Washington and the state’s planning authorities.
The usually boring motorway planning arena suddenly generated intense debates and colorful alliances.
The Libertarians joined the environmental groups in the lobbying of granting the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you travel and even possibly where you travel them – and then use that information when making tax bills.
The movement of tea in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of questions regarding privacy.
And while Congress cannot yet agree, continue or not, several states are not going to wait.
They are thinking about how over the next decade we can move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of road they travel.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes for testing, some of which have the satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
“This is not the question we may have the right to choose,” Hasan Ihrat, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to begin tracking the miles each California driver drives by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay these taxes.
Technology already exists for this.
The need for this is exacerbated by the lack of funds from the Government’s Road Construction Fund, financed by taxes that Americans pay on car fuels.
Americans don’t buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars travel more than a gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax by even one cent at high prices for gasoline.
“The gasoline tax is simply impossible to save,” said Lee Mannich, an expert on transport policy at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices were recently installed on the cars to test the error-payment system.
“This will be the best alternative in the long run,” he said.
Borrowers call this a misguided user fee.
It is not surprising that this idea attracts urban liberals, as with the help of taxes it will be possible to change the nature of travel to reduce road loads and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planning bodies in California are looking at this system as they develop strategies to achieve the targets set by the state's ambitious global warming laws.
Member of the House of Representatives Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also viewed the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market enthusiasts at Reason Fund are also thrilled that they will force drivers to pay for each mile.
“It’s not just a tax that will go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, Reason’s Vice President for Political Affairs.
People pay directly for what they get.
This movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in 2011 called for Congress to move in the direction of wrong pay.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a <0x24>90 million pilot project involving around 10,000 cars.
However, the leaders of the House of Representatives rejected the proposal because of concerns from rural legislators representing voters who often have to travel many miles in everyday life to get to work or to the city.
Several states and cities, however, are taking this route on their own.
The biggest enthusiasm is expressed in Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are involved in the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the state for mileage instead of a gasoline tax.
The pilot project in Nevada has been completed.
In New York, it is being considered.
Illinois will try it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport departments of 17 East Coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how they can implement these changes.
This concept has not received universal recognition.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track each step.
“Concerns about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and efficiency management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn’t what people wanted.
As the tests went on, the U.S. Civil Liberties Union office in Nevada warned on its website: “It will not be difficult to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, bulky technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to keep records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of the few states where it is difficult to search for inexpensive technology that would allow the state authorities to account for car miles, but without information about location and time.
If you can do this, Han said, society will feel more relaxed.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to a small, young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, the company did not contribute to the collection of state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market of car insurance, in which drivers pay on the basis of the run.
But the devices it tests attract road designers because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information that is periodically loaded using a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
