Or they can completely abandon the device, instead deciding to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state travel.
In other places, they hope to sell the idea to a cautious public, forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York City, transport officials seek to develop a taxable device that will also accept payments on parking counters, provide “pay as you drive” insurance and collect a pool of data on speed to be taken out in real time from other drivers who would drive the car.
“Automobilists will be attracted to the participation of the benefits that they will offer,” — says the document of urban design.
Some transport system designers, however, are wondering if all the talk about mispayment is just a huge distraction.
In the San Francisco Bay City Transport Commission, officials say the Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the Trusted Road Construction Fund by raising gasoline taxes.
