Goldman Sachs warns of risks to the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs warned of rising risks for the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia – consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of unpaid consumer loans and a massive reduction in the number of employees.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather the structure of this growth.
Recently, it has been completely influenced by consumption, which almost does not ease turnover,” Goldman Sachs chief economist for Russia Clemens Grafe said, presenting a quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Currently, the nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
With 6% inflation, it will be able to provide future consumer demand around the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is declining, so they are likely to optimize the cost of personnel.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages increase by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - Mr Grafe explained.
The companies faced a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to dismissals and an increase in unemployment.
The Russian business cannot raise wages, comments the chief economist of Barclays Capital on Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment near historical minimums, competition for workers is high.
In order to trick employees from the side or keep the current one, employers have to raise salaries.
Consumption in Russia supports a very rapid growth in consumer credit.
In the view of Mr. Grafe, due to the extremely high rates of consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplicative effect on the economy of the country.
“We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer loans, money is not spent on the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem in the other is that Goldman Sachs expects an increase in overdue loans.
They are mostly taken by poor people who have nothing to provide for.
The interest rates on such loans are high.
As a result, they are not returned more often,” Mr. Grafe noted.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of unpaid loans.
The director of the Banking Institute Vasily Soldokov already sees signs of an aging banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, having no access to the cheap resources that state banks have, have been forced to attract the funds of the population at high interest rates.
In response, the state banks went on the path of war and began to lower credit rates, the economist continues.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rate, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not give up dumping, Russia will face a full-fledged banking crisis, says Vasily Soldokov.
The deprivation of licenses by a number of banks in recent weeks has been seen by the economist as a forerunner of a mass collapse.
“State banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was initially not designed for a systemic crisis,” the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow and without the crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, - due to the refusal to index the wages of civil servants and military, as set out in the current version of the draft budget.
The impact on consumption will partially be mitigated by the freezing of natural monopoly tariffs (and, as a result, a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and the prerequisites for this are not yet - see the report), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is confident.
Vladimir Pantushin of Barclays Capital has not yet seen the prerequisites for the realization of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still a drop in oil prices,” he says.
According to his estimates, Russia’s economy will begin to decline at a price of oil below <0x24>90/barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the central bank is not yet in a position to lower interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has fallen, and banks have begun to raise rates.
This could mean that they didn’t believe the CB that announced the transition to targeting inflation,” said Clemens Grafe.
The interest rate policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
"For the CB, it is the collapse of all hopes," said Clemens Grafe.
The money received at the auctions of the ECB is used by banks not to lend the economy, but to manage its liquidity.
As soon as the rate drops, the exchange rate changes immediately, which means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later the ECB will realize that this strategy does not work,” Grafe said, reminding that the state plans to release the ruble into “free shipping” by the end of 2015.
But it will either have to do it earlier, or raise the key rate of the CB (5.5%), he believes.
According to his estimate, the price of the ruble is now artificially exceeded by 10%.
The ruble has only one way to lose weight, the expert concludes.
But if the central bank plunges into the finances at least a shadow of doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy of weakening the ruble, it can crush the ruble much more strongly.
