The gene of speech proved to be a stimulant for the formation of synapses
Scientists from John Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein through which the “speech gene” Foxp2 performs its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the magazine you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who were unable to say words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
Scientists found that members of the family had been disrupted by the work of the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function remains unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least part of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulant for the formation of new synapses in the brain related to speech formation.
It does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, with only Foxp2 being used for its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 really affects vocalization has been confirmed by scientists in a mouse experiment.
When the gene activity in animals was artificially reduced, they shouted less when separated from the mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the sounds being released was also restored.
Previously, the mouse was also shown a link to the vocalization of Foxp2.
Animals who introduced a human copy of the gene ate more actively and at a lower frequency than ordinary mice.
To date, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and SRPX2, respectively, is related to purely “mechanical” sound-forming properties or more subtle processes.
