Scientists have shed light on how the tail movements of the dog are related to its mood.
Earlier studies have shown that happy dogs tilt the tail to the right (from a dog’s point of view), while anxious dogs tilt the tail primarily to the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the dog’s family may notice these subtle differences in howling the tail and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trento, says: “It is well known that the left and right sides of the brain are differently involved in the formation of stimulants that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this and other species.
He added that just like humans, the right part of the brain in dogs controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the diverse tails of other dogs, the researchers watched the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analyzed their behavior.
Probably soon we will understand why their tails sometimes go in one direction, and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed dogs video with dogs — either naturalistic versions or silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and direct the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw that in the rest the expressive dog moved the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog’s beating tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail leaned predominantly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog’s beating tail), their heartbeat was learned and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that the dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience, which movements they should worry about, and which ones do not.
He notes: “If there are several encounters with other dogs, and often their tailing in one direction is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts on the basis of this experience.”
Researchers say these findings can give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, an inviting scientist at the University of Bristol Veterinary School, said it was not the first study to check whether the left and right sides are important for dogs.
Last year, a team of scientists from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a satisfied dog.
And in another research at the University of Victoria, Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail was squeezed to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming annoyed.”
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is enough evidence in different mammals that two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon understand why their tails are sometimes directed in one direction, and sometimes in the other.
