A trip through dirt, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. George Bwelle provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend, receiving hundreds of patients.
In this West African country there are not so many doctors — only one in 5,000 people
Vote here or via your mobile device.
Dr. George Bwell is one of CNN’s top 10 characters of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to make him the Hero of the Year on CNN.
This man will get <0x24>250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, George Bwelle saw his father return to life and return to his unconscious state, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a 1981 car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded him of himself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said George Bwell.
If we had the money, we would have taken it out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father in overcrowded clinics and hospitals for years, receiving any treatment they could get.
"It's not easy," said Bwelle.
“You can leave home at 5 a.m. and go to the hospital to be the first, but you’re not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation hasn't changed much since Father Bwell's death in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if the Cameroons could go to the doctor, many of them would not have it in their pockets.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of healthcare costs are private.
“The only problem with them is poverty,” Bwelle said.
And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. George Bwell and his team of volunteers carried out 700 free operations.
He himself became a doctor and worked as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people get into vans, tie medical equipment to the roofs, and go across the countryside to visit the villagers in need of help.
They are not always accompanied by luck.
Many times they had to push the cars through the rivers and dirt.
But when they come, they are met as real heroes: it’s a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that only the locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages is indeed a reason for the holiday, and Bwelle with his wide smile and unlimited energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade began receiving hundreds of patients.
“We accept 500 people on every trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the county within a radius of 60 kilometers of the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these clinics on the weekend provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get skulls, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – documents needed for school that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the brigade performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Surgery usually takes place in a school building, municipality, or home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative zone to free up space for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate operating and sanitary equipment, Bwell and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It’s an unstoppable pace, but the purpose of the brigade usually helps to support the village musicians.
“They beat the drums all night, so we wake up and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade are sent back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroon doctors and foreign medical students, has conducted 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can be of enormous importance to those they are helping.
One person explained that the free surgery he received to treat the fungus will allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these clinical receptions on weekends and working at the hospital, surgeon Bwell also works at nights in private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he said, that provides 60% of the funding of his non-profit organization; the remaining funds are covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-grade medical student at the University of Dresden in Philadelphia, a volunteer at the Bwell Group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses like O'Malley coming from the United States and Europe to join Bwell in carrying out his tasks, this is an opportunity to practice what they would never get at home.
“We were given the opportunity to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or hold tools for Dr. Bwell,” O’Malley said.
As a high school student, you would never get such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay their own trip to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medications.
But upon their arrival in Yaoundé, their food, transportation and training pay Bwell.
"He's a hero, no doubt," O'Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, the almost constant load of work is not a difficult test.
Helping others to live a happy life, fulfilling this promise to their father is what brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle said.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see what you can do to help.
