The agency "Rosbalt" deprived of media status for non-censorship
On October 31, Mosgorsud decided to recognize the invalid license for the registration of the agency "Rosbalt", - writes "Lenta".
On the deprivation of the agency of media status, Roskomnadzor insisted on systematic and gross violations of the law on media.
In the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court deemed it possible to close the media, effectively refusing to issue counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"?
The Rosbalt Information Agency was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also operates representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and operated as a federal information and analytics agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, "Rosbalt" has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency's exclusive publications were (and are still being made) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the proximity of the publication to the power structures continued throughout the agency's existence.
In addition to the fact that "Rosbalt" had an extensive base of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions was also said that Natalia Chaplin, the wife of Victor Cherkesov, was at the head of the project.
At the same time, the role of Chaplina in the leadership of "Rosbalt" is not entirely clear: she is most often called the "project manager".
The director general of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief - Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not figured in the ratings of the federal media - neither by quoting nor by the audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the ranking of visitability of Russian media sites according to the LiveInternet version.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of rosbalt.ru is about 150,000 unique visitors (and up to 500,000 views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are remarks about the helplessness of the Kremlin in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and the joke", the pogroms in the capital Biryuleva.
The Rosbalta conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when an amendment to the media law entered into force, which prohibited journalists from being censored.
The agency found a banned vocabulary in two published on the website of the agency of video clips ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot defiled the oil peaks").
The other sides are described differently.
Roskomnadzor on the basis of the detected video materials accused Rosbalt of a gross and systematic violation of the media law and appealed to the court with a request to remove the license from the agency.
In "Rosbalt" stated that the claims of the department are unlawful: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the mother words in them were masked, and, thirdly, immediately after warning the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor's claims to the World Court - and when Mosgorsud accepted Roskomnadzor's claim on 22 October 2013, the proceedings continued.
However, already 25 of the world's judges have decided not in favor of "Rosbalt": the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the Code of Administrative Offences and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each film.
Obviously, this has prevented the outcome of the hearing in Mosgorsud - if you give up the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to declare the certificate of registration of "Rosbalt" invalid, effectively depriving the agency of media status.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by the deputies of the State Duma (the application to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted on the initiative of the KPRF).
The illegitimate closure of the publication was declared by the head of the Russian Union of Journalists Vsevolod Bogdanov, the president of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Human Rights Council Mikhail Fedotov.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even gave him some guarantees that the case will not come before the revocation of the license.
The court over "Rosbalt" showed: under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be the media in Russia today - a big question.
