John Kerry says in his unprecedented acknowledgment that U.S. espionage has gone “unprecedentedly far”
John Kerry demonstrated a softening of U.S. surveillance program protection tactics by making an unprecedented acknowledgement that in some cases, U.S. espionage has “walked unprecedentedly far.”
The secretary of state also admitted that he was guilty, along with Barack Obama, of being “on an autopilot” at the time of Edward Snowden’s loud disclosure of the NSA’s spy activity.
These leaks of information have put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic scandal with its allies.
Speaking on video at an open governmental conference in London, Mr. Kerry said: “There is no doubt that the president and I, as well as other members of the government, have actually perceived some of the things that are happening on the autopilot.
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage went too far, but stressed that no one’s rights were violated.
He said: “In some cases, it has gone unprecedentedly far.
And the president is determined to shed light on this issue and explain it to the people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis to ensure that no one has a sense of abuse.
I assure you, there are no abuses against innocent people in this process.”
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA acted out of good motives and that his surveillance operations saved many lives.
He added: “We are working in a new world where people are ready to explode.
There is radical extremism in the world, unreasonable and full of determination to kill people, blast people and attack governments.
What if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
“We were actually preventing aircraft crashes, explosions of buildings and killing people because we were able to learn about these plans in advance.”
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will be heading to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. espionage abroad and convince Europeans to continue joint anti-terrorism efforts with the U.S., the chairman of the Senate’s Subcommittee on European Affairs said.
Connecticut senator Chris Murphy said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorist organizations due to disappointment in connection with the National Security Agency's surveillance.
“For the interests of U.S. national security, it is really important that Europeans remain our supporters of our common anti-terrorism efforts,” said Democrat Murphy, who serves in the first term and is chairman of the Senate’s Subcommittee on International Relations.
“And I’m going to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger over these NSA programs.”
The news that the NSA has collected millions of records of telephone calls in Europe has deteriorated relations with some US allies, although the head of the agency said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies.
Other disclosures included documents published by Snowden, indicating that the NSA was monitoring German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone, as well as the phones of about 34 other world leaders.
Director of National Intelligence James Clapper defended the spy activity against the allies as necessary and said it was a regular case on both sides.
Against this background, Murphy said that his office was organizing a trip of members of Congress, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped that members of both parties and both houses would join the delegation.
The names of other participating legislators should be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the travel program is still in development.
While Murphy said the trip’s goal was to improve relationships, he said some degree of “hardness from the best impulses” would also be manifested.
He said European leaders should be honest with their people in what espionage programs they have been using for years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also agree that we are not the only ones engaged in intelligence,” Murphy said.
Mr. Kerry, meanwhile, should be heading this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to address the issues of hostility towards the US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as US intelligence.
